periences of Wagner's protagonists. Sources ofparticular political significance include the fables of the eighteenth-century Venetian playwright Carlo Gozzi, the Iphigenia operas of Christoph Willibald Gluck, and the legacy of the martyr Theodor Körner, whose poetry became the lingua franca of the revolutionary movement to liberate and unify Germany. Syer's book offers fresh insights into the historical context that gave rise to Wagner's dramatic art, revealing how his distinct and powerful imagery is intimately bound up with the crises and instabilities of his era. Katherine R. Syer is associate professor of theatre and musicology at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOperazGermanyy19th century. 4aGerman History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  aDer fliegende Holländer.  aDie Feen.  aLohengrin.  aRing.  aTannhäuser.  aWagner's operas.  acultural life.  apolitical significance.  arevolutionary movement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046869540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580468695423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580468695/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles